# llama-server.service — Host-first deployment systemd unit

## Overview

This systemd unit file runs the llama-server process for the LLM proxy stack.
It uses the host-first model via `start-llama.sh` (router mode) and is designed
to be deployed as a **user service** (recommended), though a system-service
variant is documented below.

> **IMPORTANT — parallelism alignment:** The llama-server `--parallel` flag
> (controlled via the `LLAMA_PARALLEL` environment variable) MUST match the
> proxy's `session_slot_pool_size` in `proxy/config.yaml`. Mismatch causes
> slot exhaustion or restore failures.
>
> The proxy lifecycle automatically exports `LLAMA_PARALLEL` from
> `server.session_slot_pool_size`. If you set `LLAMA_PARALLEL` manually in
> this unit file, ensure it matches the proxy configuration.

## Runtime alignment: `--parallel` vs `session_slot_pool_size`

The llama-server `--parallel` (or `-np`) flag must match the proxy's
`server.session_slot_pool_size` in `proxy/config.yaml`. A mismatch causes slot
exhaustion or restore failures:

- `pool_size < --parallel` → some server slots go unused.
- `pool_size > --parallel` → sessions map to slot IDs that do not exist.

When started through the proxy (standard production path), the proxy lifecycle
automatically exports `LLAMA_PARALLEL` from `session_slot_pool_size`, and
`start-llama.sh` reads that env var. If you start llama-server directly (e.g.,
via systemd bypassing the proxy), ensure the `Environment=LLAMA_PARALLEL=N`
value matches the proxy's `session_slot_pool_size` value.

## User Service (Recommended)

This is the recommended deployment approach for single-operator setups. It
keeps the llama-server process under the operator's login session.

**File location**: `~/.config/systemd/user/llama-server.service`

```ini
[Unit]
Description=LLM llama-server (host-first, router mode)
After=network.target
Wants=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/start-llama.sh router
Environment=LLAMA_MODELS_PRESET=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/models.ini
Environment=LLAMA_MODELS_MAX=1
Environment=LLAMA_SERVER_BIN=/usr/local/bin/llama-server
Environment=HSA_OVERRIDE_GFX_VERSION=11.5.1
Environment=ROCM_LLVM_PRE_VEGA=1
Environment=PORT=8080

# Restart policy
Restart=always
RestartSec=5

# Logging
StandardOutput=append:/home/rgardler/.local/state/llama-server/logs/llama-server.log
StandardError=append:/home/rgardler/.local/state/llama-server/logs/llama-server.log

# Resource limits
MemoryMax=70G
CPUQuota=200%

# Security hardening
NoNewPrivileges=false
ProtectSystem=false
ProtectHome=false

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
```

### Setup commands (user service)

```bash
# Create log directory
mkdir -p ~/.local/state/llama-server/logs

# Enable and start the service
systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable llama-server.service
systemctl --user start llama-server.service

# Check status
systemctl --user status llama-server.service

# View logs
journalctl --user -u llama-server.service -f
```

## System Service (Alternative)

Use this approach only if the llama-server must survive logout or run
independently of any user session. This requires root or sudo access.

**File location**: `/etc/systemd/system/llama-server.service`

```ini
[Unit]
Description=LLM llama-server (host-first, router mode)
After=network.target
Wants=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=rgardler
Group=rgardler
WorkingDirectory=/home/rgardler/projects/llm
ExecStart=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/start-llama.sh router
Environment=LLAMA_MODELS_PRESET=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/models.ini
Environment=LLAMA_MODELS_MAX=1
Environment=LLAMA_SERVER_BIN=/usr/local/bin/llama-server
Environment=HSA_OVERRIDE_GFX_VERSION=11.5.1
Environment=ROCM_LLVM_PRE_VEGA=1
Environment=PORT=8080

Restart=always
RestartSec=5

StandardOutput=append:/var/log/llama-server/llama-server.log
StandardError=append:/var/log/llama-server/llama-server.log

MemoryMax=70G
CPUQuota=200%

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

### Setup commands (system service)

```bash
# Create log directory
sudo mkdir -p /var/log/llama-server
sudo chown rgardler:rgardler /var/log/llama-server

# Install the unit
sudo cp llama-server.service /etc/systemd/system/
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable llama-server.service
sudo systemctl start llama-server.service

# Check status
sudo systemctl status llama-server.service

# View logs
sudo journalctl -u llama-server.service -f
```

## Verification

Regardless of deployment approach, verify the service is running:

```bash
# Check health endpoint
curl http://localhost:8080/health

# Expected response:
# {
#   "status": "healthy",
#   "ready": true,
#   "current_model": null,
#   "llama_server_running": true,
#   "backend_signals": {
#     "connect_failures": 0,
#     "read_failures": 0,
#     "timeout_failures": 0,
#     "other_failures": 0,
#     "concurrency_rejects": 0
#   }
# }

# Check loaded models
curl http://localhost:8080/models
```

## Log paths

- **User service**: `$XDG_STATE_HOME/llama-server/logs/llama-server.log` (typically `~/.local/state/llama-server/logs/llama-server.log`)
- **System service**: `/var/log/llama-server/llama-server.log`

